Bilateral diffuse infiltrates are seen with pneumonia caused by viruses, P. jirovecii, L. pneumophila, and occasionally M. pneumoniae. C. pneumoniae, C. psittaci, Coxiella burnetii, and M. pneumoniae can cause patchy alveolar infiltrates, which are out of proportion to clinical findings (Figure 34-1
). Distinctly confined lobar or segmental abnormality or a large pleural effusion suggests bacterial infection (Figure 34-2
) and, rarely, M. pneumoniae or adenovirus infections.60, 61, 62 Round appearance of infiltrate, common in children <8 years of age, most often is due to S. pneumoniae.
